CHAPTER 1 \'96 INTRODUCTION\
1.1 Background\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 In the rapidly evolving field of software development, developers and students constantly encounter technical challenges that require prompt, accurate solutions. Traditional search engines often return outdated or irrelevant results, while dedicated platforms like Stack Overflow have revolutionised how technical knowledge is shared. Bug Overflow was conceptualised to demonstrate this collaborative Q&A model through a fully functional implementation using modern web technologies.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 The platform was born out of the recognition that a well-designed Q&A system can significantly reduce the time developers spend solving problems by leveraging the collective intelligence of a community. By implementing a reputation and badge system, the platform incentivises high-quality contributions and expert participation.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1.2 Objective\
To build a fully functional developer Q&A platform modelled on Stack Overflow.\
To implement secure user authentication using JWT tokens and HTTP-only cookies.\
To develop a reputation-based reward system that encourages quality contributions.\
To create a rich-text editor for formatting questions, answers, and articles.\
To implement real-time notifications for user interactions.\
To design a scalable RESTful API backend using Node.js and Express.js.\
To integrate MongoDB as the primary database for flexible data storage.\
To demonstrate expertise in full-stack web development using the MERN stack.\
1.3 Purpose\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The purpose of Bug Overflow is to provide a platform where developers, students, and technology enthusiasts can collaboratively solve technical problems. It serves as a knowledge base that grows organically through community contributions. The platform aims to reduce the time spent on debugging and problem-solving by providing a structured, searchable repository of questions and verified answers.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1.4 Scope\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Bug Overflow covers the following functional areas:\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \'95 User Management: Registration, login, profile management, and reputation tracking.\u8232 \'95 Question Management: Posting, editing, deleting, tagging, and searching questions.\u8232 \'95 Answer Management: Submitting, editing, voting, and accepting answers.\u8232 \'95 Comment System: Threaded discussions on questions and answers.\u8232 \'95 Article Publishing: Writing and sharing technical articles.\u8232 \'95 Notifications: Real-time alerts for votes, answers, and comments.\u8232 \'95 Bookmarks: Saving questions for later reference.\u8232 \'95 Reputation & Badges: Automated reputation and badge award system.\u8232 \'95 Search: Full-text search across questions and tags.\u8232 \u8232 The platform is designed as a web application accessible through modern browsers. It is not currently designed for mobile-native applications, though the responsive design makes it usable on mobile browsers.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1.5 Applicability\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Bug Overflow is applicable in the following contexts:\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \'95 Educational Institutions: As a platform for students to discuss coursework and programming doubts.\u8232 \'95 Development Teams: As an internal knowledge base for technical Q&A within organisations.\u8232 \'95 Online Communities: As a community hub for technology interest groups.\u8232 \'95 Freelancers & Hobbyists: As a personal learning and problem-solving resource.\u8232 \'95 Academic Research: As a case study for MERN stack application development and gamification.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1.6 Achievements\
Successfully implemented a full MERN stack web application with 8+ modules.\
Designed and deployed a RESTful API with 40+ endpoints across 8 resource domains.\
Implemented JWT-based authentication with refresh token rotation and HTTP-only cookie storage.\
Built a gamified reputation system with automated badge awards at milestone thresholds.\
Integrated a rich-text editor supporting code blocks, bold, italic, links, and lists.\
Developed a real-time notification system with unread count tracking.\
Implemented rate limiting using express-rate-limit to prevent API abuse.\
Created responsive UI using React with React Router for client-side navigation.\
Designed a comprehensive MongoDB schema with 8 data models and relationship management.\
1.7 Organisation of Report\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 This report is structured to provide a comprehensive overview of the Bug Overflow project from conception to implementation. The following chapters are organised as follows:\uc0\u8232 \u8232 Chapter 1 \'96 Introduction: Provides background, objectives, scope, and applicability.\u8232 Chapter 2 \'96 Survey of Technologies: Reviews the technologies used in development.\u8232 Chapter 3 \'96 Requirements and Analysis: Covers problem definition, requirements, and planning.\u8232 Chapter 4 \'96 System Design: Presents data models, diagrams, and UI screenshots.\u8232 Chapter 5 \'96 Implementation and Testing: Details the development process and test results.\u8232 Chapter 6 \'96 Results and Discussion: Presents the working system and user documentation.\u8232 Chapter 7 \'96 Conclusion: Summarises achievements, limitations, and future scope.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \page \
CHAPTER 2 \'96 SURVEY OF TECHNOLOGIES\
2.1 React.js (Frontend Framework)\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 React.js is a JavaScript library developed and maintained by Meta (formerly Facebook) for building user interfaces. It follows a component-based architecture where the UI is broken into independent, reusable components. React uses a Virtual DOM to efficiently update only the parts of the page that have changed, resulting in fast and responsive user interfaces.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 In Bug Overflow, React is used for all frontend views including the home page, question detail, user profile, and article pages. React Router v6 provides client-side navigation without page reloads, creating a smooth Single Page Application (SPA) experience. State management is handled through React Context API and component-level state with useState and useEffect hooks.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 2.2 Node.js (Runtime Environment)\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Node.js is an open-source, cross-platform JavaScript runtime environment built on Chrome's V8 JavaScript engine. It enables server-side execution of JavaScript, allowing the use of a single programming language for both frontend and backend development.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 Bug Overflow's server is built on Node.js with ES Module syntax (import/export). Node's non-blocking I/O model makes it highly suitable for handling concurrent API requests from multiple users simultaneously, which is essential for a community platform.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 2.3 Express.js (Web Framework)\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Express.js is a minimal and flexible Node.js web application framework that provides a robust set of features for building web and mobile applications. It simplifies routing, middleware integration, and request/response handling.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 In Bug Overflow, Express.js handles all HTTP routing, middleware (authentication, rate limiting, CORS), and request processing. The application uses express-rate-limit to prevent brute-force attacks on authentication endpoints, with a limit of 100 requests per 15-minute window.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 2.4 MongoDB & Mongoose (Database)\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 MongoDB is a NoSQL document-oriented database that stores data in flexible, JSON-like BSON documents. Unlike relational databases, MongoDB's schema-less nature allows for rapid iteration and easy handling of complex nested data structures.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 Mongoose is an Object Data Modelling (ODM) library for MongoDB and Node.js that provides a schema-based solution for modelling application data. Bug Overflow uses Mongoose for all 8 data models: User, Question, Answer, Comment, Article, Notification, Bookmark, and Tag.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 2.5 JSON Web Tokens (JWT) \'96 Authentication\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 JSON Web Tokens (JWT) is an open standard (RFC 7519) for securely transmitting information between parties as a JSON object. JWTs are digitally signed using a secret key, making them verifiable and trustworthy.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 Bug Overflow uses JWT for stateless authentication. Upon login, an access token and refresh token are generated. Access tokens (15-minute expiry) are stored in HTTP-only cookies to prevent XSS attacks. Refresh tokens (7-day expiry) allow session continuation without re-authentication. The authentication middleware verifies the JWT signature on every protected API call.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 2.6 React Quill (Rich Text Editor)\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 React Quill is a React component that wraps the Quill.js rich text editor. It provides a WYSIWYG editing experience with support for text formatting (bold, italic, underline), lists, code blocks, links, images, and more.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 Bug Overflow uses React Quill for the question editor, answer editor, and article editor. The formatted content is stored as HTML in MongoDB and rendered safely using DOMPurify sanitisation to prevent XSS injection attacks.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 2.7 Nodemailer (Email Service)\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Nodemailer is a module for Node.js that allows easy email sending. It supports SMTP transport and works with popular email providers.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 Bug Overflow uses Nodemailer for sending account-related emails including password reset links and welcome notifications. The mailer utility in server/utils/mailer.js configures the transport and provides a reusable send function.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 2.8 Bcrypt.js (Password Hashing)\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Bcrypt.js is a JavaScript library that implements the bcrypt password-hashing algorithm. Bcrypt uses a salt to protect against rainbow table attacks and is intentionally slow to compute, making brute-force attacks impractical.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 All user passwords in Bug Overflow are hashed using bcrypt before storage in MongoDB. The authentication controller uses bcrypt.compare() to verify login credentials without ever storing or transmitting plain-text passwords.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
